      "scripts": [
        {
          "number": 1,
          "script": "Welcome to this course on training data poisoning. Before we get into the technical detail, let's establish what we're actually talking about and why it matters. Every AI system learns from data, and that data is essentially its foundation. If someone deliberately corrupts or manipulates that data, even in small, subtle ways, the AI can start behaving in ways that are genuinely harmful. And here's the thing: this isn't just a theoretical concern discussed in research papers. Real organisations, in sectors like healthcare and finance, are already dealing with this threat right now. What makes it particularly tricky is that the changes can be tiny, almost invisible, yet the knock-on effects on the AI's behaviour can be significant. By the end of this lesson, you'll have a solid grounding in what data poisoning actually is, which means you'll be far better placed to spot the warning signs before any real damage is done. Let's get started."
        },
        {
          "number": 2,
          "script": "These examples might surprise you, because poisoning attacks are not just theoretical. They have already happened in the real world. Perhaps the most famous case is Microsoft's Tay chatbot, which was manipulated within hours of launch simply by users feeding it harmful content. Spam filters have also been fooled, with attackers gradually slipping mislabelled emails into training data until the filter stopped recognising junk altogether. In healthcare, researchers have shown that tiny, almost invisible changes to medical scan images can skew how a model makes diagnoses. Recommendation systems are another target, where fake user behaviour is used to push certain products unfairly. Even facial recognition tools have been degraded through poisoned datasets introduced during open data collection drives. And here is the important point: in many of these cases, the attack was entirely avoidable with the right precautions in place. That is exactly what this course is going to help you understand."
        },
        {
          "number": 3,
          "script": "So let's look at the different ways that poisoned data can actually find its way into a training pipeline. The most straightforward method is simply mislabelling, where examples in your dataset are tagged with the wrong category, either by accident or deliberately. Then you have outright fabrication, where an attacker injects entirely fake rows of data into your dataset. With image-based models, corrupted or subtly altered image files can carry hidden patterns that skew what the model learns. Web scraping is another big one, because if you're pulling text from the internet at scale, you have very little control over what's in it, and bad actors can seed content online specifically to be scraped up. And finally, there's the insider threat, where someone with legitimate access to your data pipeline manipulates it from the inside. These aren't just theoretical scenarios. Each of these vectors has been demonstrated in real research, and understanding them is the first step towards defending against them."
        },
        {
          "number": 4,
          "script": "Let's look at some real examples of training data poisoning, because this isn't just a theoretical concern. One of the most well-known cases is Microsoft's Tay chatbot, which was launched in 2016 and had to be shut down within a single day. Attackers simply chatted with it, feeding it racist and abusive messages through perfectly normal interactions, and the model learned from all of it. That's what makes this so unsettling: it looked completely innocent from the outside. We've also seen this in healthcare, where medical imaging models have been misled by deliberately mislabelled training scans, which can seriously affect how accurately a system diagnoses patients. And spam filters have been quietly manipulated so that malicious emails slip straight through. The pattern you'll notice across all of these is that the attacks were small and gradual. A slow drip of bad data is often far more damaging than one obvious, large-scale intrusion."
        },
        {
          "number": 5,
          "script": "So let's look at some real-world examples, because this isn't just a theoretical problem. Perhaps the most famous case is Microsoft's Tay chatbot, which was manipulated by users who deliberately fed it offensive content, and within just a few hours it was producing racist responses. That's a striking example of how quickly things can go wrong. In the physical world, researchers demonstrated that simply sticking small patterns onto stop signs could fool self-driving car systems into misclassifying them entirely, which is genuinely alarming from a safety perspective. We've also seen spam filters undermined by attackers who cleverly disguised junk mail to look legitimate, and medical imaging models thrown off by incorrectly labelled training scans. Even recommendation systems aren't safe, with fake reviews injected at scale to manipulate what gets promoted. The consequences across all of these cases are serious: biased outputs, safety failures, and significant reputational damage for the organisations involved. These aren't edge cases; they're warnings."
        },
        {
          "number": 6,
          "script": "So let's talk about what actually happens when poisoned data makes its way into real systems, because the consequences can be genuinely serious. Imagine a hiring tool that's been trained on skewed data. It starts rejecting perfectly qualified candidates simply because of patterns baked in during training. Or think about a medical diagnosis system that's learned from corrupted records. Suddenly it's pointing doctors in completely the wrong direction, and that puts patients at risk. In financial services, fraud detection models that have been tampered with can start missing the very threats they were built to catch. Chatbots trained on manipulated text can confidently spread misinformation to thousands of people at once. And perhaps most alarmingly, self-driving vehicles that have learned from poisoned image data might misread a stop sign entirely. These aren't just technical glitches. They're real-world harms affecting real people. That's why understanding how this happens is so important."
        },
        {
          "number": 7,
          "script": "So now that we understand how data poisoning works, let's talk about what you can actually do to protect yourself. The good news is that there are some practical steps you can take, even if you're not a security expert. First, make a habit of regularly checking where your training data is coming from, and look out for anything that seems unusual or out of place, like duplicate records or entries that just don't fit the pattern. It's also worth controlling who has permission to contribute data in the first place, because limiting access reduces the risk significantly. On the technical side, anomaly detection tools can help you spot suspicious patterns automatically, which saves a lot of manual effort. And finally, before you ever kick off a training run, take the time to verify that your labels are accurate and consistent. These steps won't guarantee perfect security, but they will make your pipeline considerably harder to exploit."
        },
        {
          "number": 8,
          "script": "So let's bring everything together with the core lessons from this session. The fundamental thing to understand is that when training data is compromised, the model built on top of it will behave in ways you simply cannot trust. And what makes this particularly dangerous is that the changes causing that harm can be incredibly small and subtle. You might not even notice them at first glance. That is why verifying where your data comes from is so important, every single time, without exception. We also need to recognise that bias in a dataset is not always accidental. It can be deliberately planted by someone with malicious intent. The good news is that clean, well-managed data genuinely leads to safer, more reliable outcomes. And the most practical habit you can build right now is auditing your datasets thoroughly before any training begins. Prevention is always far easier than trying to fix a corrupted model after the fact."
        }
      ]
    }
